This paper deals with computing nearest neighbors approximately, which is a central problem in large-scale data mining. It has applications in machine learning and data science, which suggests that it could belong to the sub-category of cs.LG (Machine Learning). The paper also discusses distance functions that measure the distance between two probability distributions, which could fall under the sub-category of cs.IT (Information Theory). Additionally, the paper proposes a general framework for designing LSH schemes for f-divergence distance functions, which could be classified under the sub-category of cs.DS (Data Structures and Algorithms). The paper also mentions applications such as model compression, which could suggest that it belongs to the sub-category of cs.AI (Artificial Intelligence). Finally, the paper discusses the use of LSH schemes in computer vision, which could indicate that it belongs to the sub-category of cs.CV (Computer Vision and Pattern Recognition).
